- Compounds of the Group 2 elements are used to colour fireworks.
- The small size of $\mathrm{Be}^{2+}$ (ionic radius 27 pm ) and its consequent high charge density and polarizing power results in the compounds of Be being largely covalent; the ion is a strong Lewis acid.

The coordination number most commonly observed for this small atom is 4 and the local geometry tetrahedral. Beryllium's larger congeners typically have coordination numbers of 6 or more. Some consequences of these properties are:
- A significant covalent contribution to the bonding in compounds such as the beryllium halides $\mathrm{BeCl}_{2}, \mathrm{BeBr}_{2}$, and $\mathrm{BeI}_{2}$ and the hydride, $\mathrm{BeH}_{2}$.
- A greater tendency to form complexes, with the formation of molecular compounds such as $\mathrm{Be}_{4} \mathrm{O}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2} \mathrm{CCH}_{3}\right)_{6}$.
- Hydrolysis (deprotonation) of beryllium salts in aqueous solution, forming species such as $\left[\mathrm{Be}\left(\mathrm{OH}_{2}\right)_{3} \mathrm{OH}\right]+$ and acidic solutions. Hydrated beryllium salts tend to decompose by hydrolysis reactions, in which beryllium oxo- or hydroxo-salts are formed, rather than by the simple loss of water.
- The oxide and other chalcogenides of Be adopt structures with the more directional 4:4-coordination structures.
- Beryllium forms many stable organometallic compounds, including methylberyllium $\left(\mathrm{Be}\left(\mathrm{CH}_{3}\right)_{2}\right)$, ethylberyllium, t butylberyllium, and beryllocene ( $\left.\left(\mathrm{C}_{5} \mathrm{H}_{5}\right)_{2} \mathrm{Be}\right)$.

